This was an exercise to replicate a map a friend of mine made in ArcGIS. However, the challenge for me was to use only R for the entire thing, as well as make the entire process reproducable via code. Check it out:


The criteria used for scoring planting areas are:

  • Elevation higher than 125 feet (1 point)
  • Road density below the town average (1 point)
  • Soil designated as “Prime farmland” (3 points)
  • Land classified as a forest, brushland, orchard, cropland, or wetland (2 points)
  • Land classified as undeveloped, conserved, or protected (1 point)

For more information on the data I used, check out the source code which has links to all the datasets!


You’ll notice some slight differences between my map and the one I’m replicating, most of which came down to data sources:

  • My data classified wetlands and forest/brushland/orchard/croplands as mutually exclusive. Thus my max score is 8 instead of 10 since land can’t be both a wetland and a forest/etc.
  • We used different methods for road density. I used a raster for line density of roads and classified the cells that had a density of less than the mean as ‘Low Density’
  • Instead of using terrain datasets, my elevation data was costructed from converting contours into polygons.
  • I couldn’t find data for chemical spills so I used leaking underground storage tanks instead.
